scenario:
The macro itself does not call any <string.h> functions, so it does not by itself violate MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.17. A violation could occur if the helper metal_fmt (or the log handler) uses string.h functions unsafely. For example, if metal_fmt is implemented like:

char *metal_fmt(const char *fmt)
{
    static char buf[64];
    strcpy(buf, fmt);            /* no bounds check */
    strcat(buf, " - extra");   /* may overflow buf */
    return buf;
}

then strcpy/strcat can write beyond buf and thus violate Rule 21.17 because the string handling functions access memory beyond the destination object bounds.
